ÒâZ<?php exit; ?>a:1:{s:7:"content";O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:4:"1633";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"2";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2018-03-26 03:04:09";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2018-03-26 03:04:09";s:12:"post_content";s:10977:"<p dir="ltr">Cointelegraph got a chance to sit down and talk with Mark Edge, the man who introducedÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Ver" target="_blank" rel="nofollow,noopener">Roger Ver</a>Â to Bitcoin and the host ofÂ <a href="https://www.freetalklive.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow,noopener">Free Talk Live</a>Â radio. It was hard to miss Mark atÂ <a href="https://cointelegraph.com/news/around-4000-participants-attended-north-american-bitcoin-conference" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the North American Bitcoin Conference</a>, he was dressed in full garb and looked as if he could be a stunt-double in Monty Python and the Holy Grail. But unlike Monty Python, Mark is no joke.</p>
Markâ€™s Free Talk Live is one of the first media outlets to cover Bitcoin, and was one of the earliest members in the crypto community. Most publications did not pick up Bitcoin until around 2013Â <a href="https://www.wired.com/2011/11/mf_bitcoin/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow,noopener">with the exception of Wired, who ran a Bitcoin story in 2011</a>.

He first became involved with Bitcoin in February 2011 when the lead developer of Bitcoin,Â <a href="https://twitter.com/gavinandresen?lang=en" target="_blank" rel="nofollow,noopener">Gavin Andresen</a>, got in touch with Mark. Gavin Andresen is a software developer who graduated from Princeton in 1988 and was designated the lead developer of reference implementation by Satoshi Nakamoto.
<h2>Lunch at Thai Garden</h2>
Gavin sent Mark an email around February 8, 2011 saying that he wanted to have lunch with Mark to discuss â€œa new currencyâ€. Mark met Gavin at theÂ <a href="http://www.thethaigardengroup.com/keene_menu" target="_blank" rel="nofollow,noopener">Thai Garden in Keene, New Hampshire, United States</a>. Andresen began by giving Mark the details about the new currency and for the very first time in his life, Mark heard the word Bitcoin.

Although the world of digital assets continues to confuse people today, back in 2011 digital assets were a completely alien concept. When Gavin and Mark had lunch, Bitcoin was only two years old and had not even broken the US $1 threshold. Mark asked Gavin questions like â€œwhat is it backed byâ€ and â€œwhat if the government tries to take it down?â€ but by the end of the conversation Gavin was able to convince Mark that Bitcoin had some viability.

At the end of the meal, Andresen wanted to pay Mark in Bitcoin for the food they just ate. Andresen sent Mark 25 BTC for his meal â€“ Bitcoin was 40 cents a piece at the time and the total came to about 10 dollars.
<blockquote>
<p dir="ltr">â€œHey Mark: Can you send me one of yourÂ <a href="http://t.yesware.com/tt/ad7481d16526d477ef8f59e64d572ab3eb6366fa/70653cee1c76bc77418e0b8711f5facc/263ae347367ec215e4262afa7d1a71b7/mybitcoin.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow,noopener">mybitcoin.com</a>Â receiving addresses?Â  I</p>
<p dir="ltr">promised to pay you back in bitcoins for your lunch, and I want to</p>
<p dir="ltr">settle the debt before bitcoins get any more expensive (they were 40</p>
<p dir="ltr">cents a piece when we had lunch, they're trading for over $1 each</p>
<p dir="ltr">today).â€</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p dir="ltr">â€œFrom: Mark Edge</p>
<p dir="ltr">Date: Tue, Feb 15, 2011 at 1:40 PM</p>
<p dir="ltr">Subject: Re: Amplifier, Bitcoin developer....</p>
<p dir="ltr">To: Gavin Andresen</p>
1HVgNPFxn69MpGk3xG6w3J1Uv3EKES 4ZVE

That sounds like good news for everybody!â€</blockquote>
